@sdb7092 difference is : gawain is fictional and his skin color is neither quintessential for the fantasy story he is in, nor is it mentioned.
 If it was a religious text or a historical account (the Edda, the assassination of JFK or Boleyns story) or if the skin color was an integral component of the character (inside of the story and the notes of its creators - for example the Black Panther comics and movies) then you'd almost have a point. That is if I we disregard poetic license, artistic freedom and a few other things we could argue about for ages. 
That being said: no, I didn't like the casting choice for Boleyn.

